        <div id="tab12" class="tab-content" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="tab-tab12">
            <h2><i class="fas fa-book-open"></i> Interactive Glossary</h2>
            <p>Hover over any <span class="glossary-term">highlighted term<span class="glossary-definition">Terms like this one will show a definition when you hover.</span></span> to see its definition.</p>
            
            <div style="background:var(--bg-light); border-radius:1.5rem; padding:1.5rem; margin:2rem 0;">
                <h3>A–C</h3>
                <p>
                    <span class="glossary-term">Dehiscent<span class="glossary-definition">Seed pods or capsules that open naturally when ripe to release seeds (e.g., Acacia, Eucalyptus).</span></span> · 
                    <span class="glossary-term">Indehiscent<span class="glossary-definition">Fruits that do not open to release seeds; seeds are dispersed with the fruit (e.g., grasses, sedges).</span></span> · 
                    <span class="glossary-term">Orthodox seed<span class="glossary-definition">Seeds that can be dried to low moisture content (5-8%) and frozen for long-term storage.</span></span> · 
                    <span class="glossary-term">Recalcitrant seed<span class="glossary-definition">Seeds that cannot be dried or frozen; must be sown fresh or stored moist (e.g., many rainforest species).</span></span>
                </p>

                <h3>P–S</h3>
                <p>
                    <span class="glossary-term">Provenance<span class="glossary-definition">The original geographic source or environment of a seed lot; critical for restoration success.</span></span> · 
                    <span class="glossary-term">Phenology<span class="glossary-definition">The timing of life cycle events like flowering and fruiting in relation to climate and season.</span></span> · 
                    <span class="glossary-term">Serotinous<span class="glossary-definition">Capsules or cones that require heat (from fire) to open and release seeds (e.g., Banksia, Hakea).</span></span> · 
                    <span class="glossary-term">Biosecurity<span class="glossary-definition">Practices to prevent the spread of pests and diseases between sites (cleaning tools, footwear, vehicles).</span></span>
                </p>

                <h3>T–Z</h3>
                <p>
                    <span class="glossary-term">Threatened species<span class="glossary-definition">Species listed as endangered, vulnerable or rare under legislation; special permits required for collection.</span></span> · 
                    <span class="glossary-term">Take (legal)<span class="glossary-definition">Under Tasmanian law, includes collecting, damaging, or interfering with native plants or plant parts.</span></span> · 
                    <span class="glossary-term">Viability<span class="glossary-definition">The percentage of seeds that are alive and capable of germinating under suitable conditions.</span></span>
                </p>
            </div>

            <h3>Full Glossary</h3>
            <table class="tool-matrix">
                <tr><th style="width:200px;">Term</th><th>Definition</th></tr>
                <tr><td><strong>Biosecurity</strong></td><td>Practices to prevent the spread of pests and diseases between sites – includes cleaning tools, footwear, and vehicles with 70% ethanol or 1% bleach.</td></tr>
                <tr><td><strong>Dehiscent</strong></td><td>Seed pods or capsules that open naturally when ripe to release seeds. Common in Type B fruits (Acacia, Eucalyptus).</td></tr>
                <tr><td><strong>Indehiscent</strong></td><td>Fruits that do not open to release seeds; seeds are dispersed while still inside the fruit. Common in Type C fruits (grasses, sedges).</td></tr>
                <tr><td><strong>Orthodox seed</strong></td><td>Seeds that can be dried to low moisture content (5-8%) and frozen for long-term storage. Most Australian native seeds are orthodox.</td></tr>
                <tr><td><strong>Phenology</strong></td><td>The study of cyclic and seasonal natural phenomena, especially in relation to climate and plant life. Critical for timing seed collection.</td></tr>
                <tr><td><strong>Provenance</strong></td><td>The original geographic source or environment of a seed lot. Using local provenance seed increases survival rates in restoration.</td></tr>
                <tr><td><strong>Recalcitrant seed</strong></td><td>Seeds that cannot be dried or frozen; they remain high in moisture and must be sown fresh or stored short-term in moist conditions. Examples: rainforest species like Nothofagus.</td></tr>
                <tr><td><strong>Serotinous</strong></td><td>Capsules or cones that require heat (typically from bushfire) to open and release seeds. Examples: Banksia, Hakea, some Eucalypts.</td></tr>
                <tr><td><strong>Take (legal)</strong></td><td>Under Tasmanian legislation, includes collecting, damaging, destroying, or interfering with native plants or plant parts on reserved land or for threatened species.</td></tr>
                <tr><td><strong>Threatened species</strong></td><td>Plant or animal species listed as endangered, vulnerable, or rare under state or Commonwealth legislation. Collection requires a permit regardless of land tenure.</td></tr>
                <tr><td><strong>Viability</strong></td><td>The percentage of seeds in a lot that are alive and capable of germinating under suitable conditions. Tested via cut test, float test, or germination trial.</td></tr>
            </table>
        </div>

